http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/BIFFes-off-to-a-flying-start-in-Mysuru/article14025867.ece

The city’s date with international cinema —the eight edition of the Bengaluru International Film Festival (BIFFes) — began with the screening of award-winning Kannada film Thithi at the Kalamandira here on Thursday. Over a 100 films will be screened during the festival at four screens in INOX Multiplex, Mall of Mysore.The film schedule listed for screening starting Friday has been announced and is available on the website www.biffes.in. The festival concludes on February 5.Starting Friday, the screening at Screen 1 commences at 10 a.m. Within a gap of 10 minutes each, the films will be screened at the remaining screens — Screen 2 (at 10.10 a.m.), Screen 3 (10.20 a.m.) and Screen 4 (10.30 a.m.). The subsequent screening schedule at Screen 1 is as follows – 12.30 p.m.; 3 p.m.; 5.30 p.m. and 7.45 p.m. Screen 2 – 12.45 p.m.; 3.15 p.m.; 5.45 p.m. and 8 p.m. Screen 3 – 1.15 p.m.; 3.45 p.m.; 6 p.m. and 8.15 p.m. Screen 4 – 1.30 p.m.; 4 p.m.; 6.15 p.m. and 8.30 p.m. There was no formal inauguration in Mysuru. The first film to be screened was Thithi, recipient of two awards at the Locarno International Film Festival. The film ran to a packed house at the Kalamandira.Banners and other colourful paraphernalia of the BIFFes greeted the film enthusiasts at INOX. The lobby was decked up to create an ambience of festivity with Mysuru hosting the film festival for the first time. The venue of the inaugural screening – Kalamandira – was also decorated with BIFFes posters and banners.A.R. Prakash, Deputy Director, Department of Information and Public Relations, Mysuru, who is coordinating the festival here, said that one cannot buy a ticket and watch a film at the festival. “Those interested need to register as a delegate … then they can watch any number of films. Registration is done only at the Vartha Bhavan on Dhanwantri Road and at INOX in Mall of Mysore,” he told The Hindu.He said that 20 films will be screened on each day at the four screens. Vishukumar, Director, Information and Public Relations, visited the venue and inspected the arrangements, on Wednesday. Only those above 18 years of age can register for the film festival by showing a valid ID card.'Thithi', an award-winning Kannada movie, was the inaugural film tobe screened